cowardice or di&s;affection, they unanimou&s;ly and earne&s;tly
recommended him as a proper object of mercy. The
Admiral him&s;elf behaved through the whole tryal with
the mo&s;t chearful compo&s;ure, &s;eemingly the effect of con|&s;cious
innocence, upon which, perhaps, he too much
relied. Even after he had heard the evidence examined
